00:14:50.224 --> 00:14:52.644
factors. Transcription factors can drive cancer.

248
00:14:53.284 --> 00:14:56.724
And then from the post-doc, starting to be, well, wait a minute, the

249
00:14:56.764 --> 00:15:00.324
receivers of those transcription factors, the chromatin remodelers

250
00:15:00.924 --> 00:15:04.624
that work with the transcription factor shown here as an activator,

251
00:15:06.104 --> 00:15:09.744
are really, in some ways, a one-two punch to how transcription is

252
00:15:09.884 --> 00:15:13.874
being controlled. And so now the lesson begins to emerge that you can either

253
00:15:13.904 --> 00:15:17.524
perturb the transcription factor or you can perturb its receiver, the

254
00:15:17.544 --> 00:15:21.524
chromatin remodeler, and these can be some of the things that will drive

255
00:15:21.604 --> 00:15:23.724
cancer onset as fast

256
00:15:24.984 --> 00:15:28.913
as ever been reported. The other things in genetically

257
00:15:28.964 --> 00:15:32.884
engineered mouse models, messing with the DNA repair pathways

258
00:15:32.964 --> 00:15:36.664
tend to lead to cancers around 40, 50, 60

259
00:15:36.724 --> 00:15:40.704
weeks. If you overexpress a transcription factor, you

260
00:15:40.744 --> 00:15:43.844
can get it again in the 10 to 15-week range.

261
00:15:43.864 --> 00:15:47.624
And so while we like to think about cancer as disrupted

262
00:15:47.644 --> 00:15:49.314
genomic stability,

263
00:15:50.244 --> 00:15:54.104
really, if you mess with the transcription lineage control,

264
00:15:54.344 --> 00:15:56.924
that's what can really give you cancer quickly.

265
00:15:57.924 --> 00:16:01.544
And so began thinking about then, might it really be that disruption of

266
00:16:01.564 --> 00:16:05.064
transcriptional control is a core mechanism driving cancer?

267
00:16:05.784 --> 00:16:09.644
And what's been going on with that chromosomal instability is rolling the dice

268
00:16:09.704 --> 00:16:13.484
until you get the right players. And so, yes, rolling the

269
00:16:13.504 --> 00:16:17.344
dice more frequently, being exposed to radiation will in fact pick up the

270
00:16:17.384 --> 00:16:20.784
frequency by which the key regulators get hit.

271
00:16:21.504 --> 00:16:25.034
But very frequently, those are now turning out to be the transcription

272
00:16:25.104 --> 00:16:28.104
machinery and chromatin regulatory machinery.

273
00:16:30.144 --> 00:16:34.064
So then I'm finishing up my post-doc and getting ready to launch my own

274
00:16:34.184 --> 00:16:36.864
lab, and there was Nancy Andrews, an investigator

275
00:16:37.804 --> 00:16:41.704
in my division. And she had just been recruited to be

276
00:16:41.724 --> 00:16:45.224
the dean of the medical school at Duke, and she knew I was

277
00:16:45.304 --> 00:16:49.164
starting my lab. And so she said, "Charlie, I'm going to tell you

278
00:16:49.224 --> 00:16:52.984
how I recruit research technicians." And she said, "Here's the

