00:17:01.624 --> 00:17:03.984
pharma companies double their salary, and you lose them.

283
00:17:04.524 --> 00:17:08.045
And so here's how I've gone at this." She wrote to

284
00:17:08.305 --> 00:17:12.024
regional colleges to recruit graduating seniors to do two

285
00:17:12.085 --> 00:17:14.805
years in the lab before grad school or medical school.

286
00:17:14.844 --> 00:17:18.624
So she handed me the email addresses of the departments of biology and

287
00:17:18.724 --> 00:17:22.285
chemistry at about a dozen liberal arts colleges

288
00:17:22.384 --> 00:17:23.463
in New England.

289
00:17:25.624 --> 00:17:29.384
And what I found was amazing. These individuals were

290
00:17:29.484 --> 00:17:33.414
really stellar folks that were excited about the future,

291
00:17:33.514 --> 00:17:37.314
excited about science, really wanted to work hard, and were

292
00:17:37.344 --> 00:17:41.264
driven and were so fun to work with as they

293
00:17:41.284 --> 00:17:43.264
would come back with new ideas

294
00:17:44.104 --> 00:17:48.014
and thinking about the science, not being a pair of hands at the

295
00:17:48.084 --> 00:17:51.934
bench. And this really then, as I

296
00:17:51.944 --> 00:17:55.914
began to invest in this more and more, career development then

297
00:17:55.924 --> 00:17:59.684
became a two-way win. So as I thought about how do I help

298
00:17:59.694 --> 00:18:03.564
these folks get into their grad school or med school of choice,

299
00:18:03.904 --> 00:18:07.864
and how do we set up these two-year positions such that it really

300
00:18:07.924 --> 00:18:09.704
tees them up for this?

301
00:18:10.764 --> 00:18:14.044
It turns around, and I'll say a little bit more about that

302
00:18:15.044 --> 00:18:15.544
coming up.

303
00:18:17.164 --> 00:18:20.833
Okay. So then I launch my own lab, and I'm thinking

304
00:18:20.924 --> 00:18:23.864
about what is this chromatin remodeler doing?

305
00:18:23.964 --> 00:18:27.904
How does it really actually work? At that point in time, it was just

306
00:18:27.944 --> 00:18:30.524
known to move nucleosomes.

307
00:18:31.784 --> 00:18:34.824
What does it normally do? What are the consequences of the

308
00:18:34.864 --> 00:18:38.164
disease-associated mutations in the SWI/SNF subunits?

309
00:18:39.404 --> 00:18:43.382
AndMight we be able to leverage this information

310
00:18:43.432 --> 00:18:47.262
to think therapeutically and about vulnerabilities from

311
00:18:47.312 --> 00:18:48.282
these mutations?

312
00:18:50.092 --> 00:18:53.872
So while that first paper was in a rare pediatric cancer, and I got

313
00:18:53.932 --> 00:18:57.412
interested in it thinking because mutations in rare pediatric

