00:19:33.342 --> 00:19:36.872
And so SWI/SNF mutations also now vary

325
00:19:37.332 --> 00:19:38.652
and somewhat surprisingly,

326
00:19:39.592 --> 00:19:43.512
maybe not so much surprising now, but the mutations also turn out

327
00:19:43.552 --> 00:19:46.502
to be the basis of neurodevelopmental disorders.

328
00:19:47.132 --> 00:19:50.812
And so a mutation in a SWI/SNF subunit that is germline heterozygous

329
00:19:50.832 --> 00:19:51.432
mutation

330
00:19:52.572 --> 00:19:53.272
leads to

331
00:19:54.392 --> 00:19:57.912
neurodevelopmental disorders, and inactivating mutations

332
00:19:57.952 --> 00:19:59.732
contribute to cancer.

333
00:20:01.272 --> 00:20:05.152
And so this complex has now emerged as a major tumor suppressor,

334
00:20:05.212 --> 00:20:08.992
and it was really exciting because it pretty much was

335
00:20:09.132 --> 00:20:10.392
not on the radar.

336
00:20:12.052 --> 00:20:15.612
In terms of cancer, it was thought about by

337
00:20:15.632 --> 00:20:19.512
transcriptional people, but this was the last thing that would be going on in

338
00:20:19.572 --> 00:20:23.272
cancer, and yet it now turns out to be not quite as frequent as

339
00:20:23.292 --> 00:20:26.552
P53 and some others, but one of the most frequently altered

340
00:20:26.612 --> 00:20:29.191
complexes. So, what's really going on?

341
00:20:30.372 --> 00:20:34.212
And so I decided to leverage that postdoc work and the models we were thinking

342
00:20:34.312 --> 00:20:37.712
about because as we sequenced those tumors,

343
00:20:38.552 --> 00:20:42.232
some work by Elizabeth McKenna, who is now the

344
00:20:42.292 --> 00:20:46.252
executive editor for "Cancer Discovery," so thinking about

345
00:20:46.292 --> 00:20:49.752
people who have gone on from grad school to have impact,

346
00:20:50.252 --> 00:20:53.632
found that these tumors had the lowest rate of

347
00:20:53.672 --> 00:20:57.092
mutations that had ever been seen at the Broad Institute at that point in time.

348
00:20:57.132 --> 00:20:58.422
As we sequenced the exomes,

349
00:20:59.232 --> 00:21:02.901
there was an average of four base pair alterations in the exome,

350
00:21:03.172 --> 00:21:06.912
one of which was always loss of SMARCB1, and the other three all appeared to be

351
00:21:06.972 --> 00:21:07.352
random.

352
00:21:08.652 --> 00:21:11.992
And these were diploid tumors. So we had this incredible

353
00:21:12.032 --> 00:21:15.852
scenario that almost appears to be a cancer

354
00:21:16.032 --> 00:21:19.972
driven by a single gene mutation, inactivating mutation.

355
00:21:20.972 --> 00:21:24.372
So what's going on there, and how can that possibly work and fit

356
00:21:24.452 --> 00:21:27.612
with prevailing paradigms of the day?

357
00:21:28.492 --> 00:21:30.572
It also brought up this real challenge.

358
00:21:30.612 --> 00:21:34.472
We all love the story of CML and Gleevec, and what it basically

359
00:21:34.492 --> 00:21:37.032
says is you get a cancer-altered mutation.

360
00:21:37.452 --> 00:21:41.272
If it's got a nice pocket and it can develop a chemical in there, you

361
00:21:41.352 --> 00:21:43.452
can really transform the outcome.

362
00:21:44.592 --> 00:21:45.872
But what are you going to do here

363
00:21:46.692 --> 00:21:49.772
when you have one gene mutant and it's gone?

364
00:21:51.052 --> 00:21:52.252
How are you going to target that,

365
00:21:53.192 --> 00:21:57.072
right? And if this actually turns out to be a mechanism that's underlying 20% of

366
00:21:57.112 --> 00:22:00.591
all cancers, we really need to think about that.

367
00:22:00.692 --> 00:22:04.152
How do you target that? So while we all love the idea of

368
00:22:04.232 --> 00:22:08.152
targeting oncogenes, we have to think more broadly about what's

369
00:22:08.192 --> 00:22:08.712
going on.

370
00:22:10.332 --> 00:22:14.292
So I want to just-- to go to the first two points,

371
00:22:14.372 --> 00:22:17.812
just a few papers to bring you up to speed to some of the

372
00:22:18.392 --> 00:22:20.412
more recent data I'm going to show.

373
00:22:20.432 --> 00:22:24.352
What we basically found was that by manipulating these and looking at

374
00:22:24.432 --> 00:22:28.352
them, that this complex is essential for enhancer function.

375
00:22:28.392 --> 00:22:32.252
It binds at enhancers, it mobilizes nucleosomes, and it enables transcription

376
00:22:32.312 --> 00:22:35.702
factors to bind and activate lineage-specific

377
00:22:35.772 --> 00:22:39.672
development. It's also at promoters, but as you disrupt

378
00:22:39.692 --> 00:22:43.152
the complex, it really harms enhancers much more than

379
00:22:43.162 --> 00:22:46.892
promoters. And then in the bottom left, we got this additional clue

380
00:22:46.932 --> 00:22:50.882
about two years ago that it turns out that certain subunits of

381
00:22:50.912 --> 00:22:54.302
this complex are actually mitotic bookmarks, meaning that as cells go through

382
00:22:54.332 --> 00:22:58.102
mitosis and the genome is completely restructured,

383
00:22:58.462 --> 00:23:02.292
they bind to DNA to help the cells remember what their fate should

384
00:23:02.332 --> 00:23:06.152
be as they exit and to enable the activation of

385
00:23:06.192 --> 00:23:09.752
genes early in G1 that are important for

386
00:23:10.232 --> 00:23:14.072
the particular cell identity at which place the SWI/SNF

387
00:23:14.152 --> 00:23:16.612
complex gets built where they are bound.

388
00:23:17.552 --> 00:23:19.432
Okay, with that as background,

389
00:23:21.232 --> 00:23:25.182
one of the things that I had thought about and been impressed by was

390
00:23:25.212 --> 00:23:29.072
reading about SWI/SNF, which was originally developed in yeast, the power of yeast

391
00:23:29.112 --> 00:23:32.992
genetics as people did screens to understand what genes were where.

392
00:23:33.032 --> 00:23:34.482
You didn't really have to know function.

393
00:23:34.932 --> 00:23:37.842
You mutagenize the yeast, and you begin to find out what's going on.

394
00:23:38.252 --> 00:23:42.072
Then that moves into Drosophila, and genetic screens in Drosophila

395
00:23:42.132 --> 00:23:44.872
begin to reveal pathways and genes that are working on.

396
00:23:45.372 --> 00:23:49.272
But mammalian systems had been far too complex to do that.

397
00:23:50.432 --> 00:23:53.842
And then one day, I was talking to Bill Hahn and Levi Garraway when I was at

398
00:23:54.092 --> 00:23:57.702
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute, and they told me about an idea they had.

399
00:23:57.712 --> 00:24:00.722
Bill had something called Project Achilles at that point in time.

400
00:24:00.752 --> 00:24:04.272
What if we take a whole bunch of cancer cell lines,

401
00:24:04.972 --> 00:24:08.872
and then we use shRNAs to turn off every gene in the genome

402
00:24:08.912 --> 00:24:12.512
one by one, and we now ask which genes are essential for

