00:28:58.864 --> 00:29:02.084
starting from scratch with a hypothesis that actually turned out to be correct.

484
00:29:02.604 --> 00:29:06.304
And so as we look at mass spec analysis of the proteins that go up

485
00:29:06.364 --> 00:29:10.104
upon DCAF5 knockdown, there were 18 proteins in the

486
00:29:10.124 --> 00:29:13.484
predetermined window, nine of which were SWI/SNF subunits.

487
00:29:13.944 --> 00:29:17.584
And so the people that do TMT profiling for a living, this was my first time

488
00:29:17.804 --> 00:29:20.384
collaborating with them, said they've never seen a result like this.

489
00:29:20.434 --> 00:29:23.744
And this was jumped off the page. Sandy went on to

490
00:29:24.364 --> 00:29:27.424
try and make sure that that was right and so did what was called

491
00:29:28.264 --> 00:29:32.084
DiGly tagging to look at which proteins

492
00:29:32.144 --> 00:29:34.884
are actually getting ubiquitinated by

493
00:29:34.924 --> 00:29:38.784
DCAF5 and found that three different SWI/SNF subunits

494
00:29:38.824 --> 00:29:40.894
at multiple different sites are

495
00:29:41.844 --> 00:29:45.514
dependent upon DCAF5 for ubiquitination.

496
00:29:46.104 --> 00:29:49.964
Okay, so this thing is really now, this DCAF5 is indeed degrading

497
00:29:50.044 --> 00:29:53.724
SWI/SNF subunits. What happens when you get rid of

498
00:29:53.764 --> 00:29:57.644
DCAF5? And so we asked about where

499
00:29:57.684 --> 00:30:01.664
it binds in the genome. And so when we turned SMARCB1 back on, we said that's going

500
00:30:01.674 --> 00:30:05.504
to be the set of where SWI/SNF should normally be.

501
00:30:05.544 --> 00:30:09.384
And then what we did was knock down DCAF5 and ask where the rest of the

502
00:30:09.404 --> 00:30:13.324
SWI/SNF subunits went, and they went exactly where they were normally supposed to.

503
00:30:14.024 --> 00:30:17.944
So the absence of SMARCB1 was not impairing the correct targeting of the

504
00:30:17.984 --> 00:30:18.524
protein.

505
00:30:19.524 --> 00:30:21.784
And so it was going back to where it was.

506
00:30:22.344 --> 00:30:26.264
And so what is the effect now of these residual complexes upon

507
00:30:27.084 --> 00:30:30.984
DCAF5 knockout? And remember, my corollary was that in the absence

508
00:30:31.024 --> 00:30:33.954
of DCAF5, these things are going to accumulate, they're going to be toxic, and

509
00:30:33.984 --> 00:30:35.514
they're going to shut down transcription.

510
00:30:36.384 --> 00:30:40.184
And then Sandy, the grad student, formerly the research technician, now the

511
00:30:40.204 --> 00:30:41.634
grad student, says, "Well, wait a minute.

512
00:30:41.764 --> 00:30:45.604
Maybe the complex actually works

513
00:30:45.704 --> 00:30:49.604
and you're rescuing its activity." And so I patiently

514
00:30:49.644 --> 00:30:53.584
explained to Sandy, remember nucleosome here, the docking site here, we're missing

515
00:30:53.644 --> 00:30:55.804
that. That's really not likely to happen.

516
00:30:56.484 --> 00:30:57.144
So we made a bet,

517
00:30:58.704 --> 00:31:02.214
and Sandy won.And so what

518
00:31:02.314 --> 00:31:05.734
happens is when we knock out DCAF5, we see the SwitchNif

519
00:31:05.834 --> 00:31:07.314
complex accumulating,

520
00:31:08.134 --> 00:31:11.974
we're picking up. Now, it's not as strong as if you turn SMARCB1

521
00:31:12.014 --> 00:31:15.734
back on. So if you rescue SMARCB1, you get a bigger peak, but you get a

522
00:31:15.794 --> 00:31:19.394
substantial increase in peak just by knocking out DCAF5.

523
00:31:19.954 --> 00:31:23.814
And then if we look at what happens to the genes that are being bound, they

524
00:31:23.834 --> 00:31:27.674
don't go down as I had hypothesized, they go up.

525
00:31:28.554 --> 00:31:31.614
So transcription is indeed being rescued.

526
00:31:32.074 --> 00:31:35.134
And depending upon the assay we used, between 30% and

527
00:31:35.374 --> 00:31:38.584
70% of wild-type activity now comes back.

528
00:31:40.034 --> 00:31:41.574
What are the genes that are upregulated?

529
00:31:41.634 --> 00:31:44.614
I won't go through it a lot, but they're basically the same genes as if you

530
00:31:44.674 --> 00:31:48.534
normally turn on SMARCB1, and they are the genes

531
00:31:48.574 --> 00:31:52.214
that are involved in normal development. And so this was a kidney model.

532
00:31:52.634 --> 00:31:54.474
Kidney development goes up.

533
00:31:56.374 --> 00:32:00.334
What happens when we go in vivo? So we did now a degrader tag

534
00:32:00.534 --> 00:32:04.464
on DCAF5, put it in, did two cycles of degrading, and

535
00:32:04.514 --> 00:32:06.314
I'd never really seen anything like that.

536
00:32:06.354 --> 00:32:08.794
It completely wiped out the tumors, and they never came back.

537
00:32:08.814 --> 00:32:11.474
We waited 100 days, and the tumors did not come back.

538
00:32:12.694 --> 00:32:16.414
So DCAF5 is essential for cancer cells.

539
00:32:17.174 --> 00:32:20.894
I didn't take time to show you this, but we made germline knockouts of the

540
00:32:20.974 --> 00:32:23.054
mice, and they're viable.

541
00:32:23.874 --> 00:32:27.604
So now we have a cancer target that wipes out a tumor so that it won't

542
00:32:27.634 --> 00:32:31.294
come back, and yet the knockout mice are viable.

543
00:32:31.334 --> 00:32:35.014
They're born at Mendelian ratio. They turn out to be slightly smaller than

544
00:32:35.614 --> 00:32:38.434
the wild-type mice, and there's a small amount of neonatal lethality.

545
00:32:39.124 --> 00:32:42.674
But if we think about the drugs that we use in the clinic now to treat cancer,

546
00:32:42.754 --> 00:32:45.924
they're all pretty much targeting essential genes, things like

547
00:32:45.954 --> 00:32:49.834
microtubules and others. Here we get something that has a very

548
00:32:49.934 --> 00:32:51.114
mild phenotype.

549
00:32:52.534 --> 00:32:56.084
Is this actually targetable? So it turns out it is in a family of

550
00:32:56.154 --> 00:32:58.734
genes that have been proven to be targetable.

551
00:32:58.954 --> 00:33:02.834
In working with Eric Fisher's lab at Dana-Farber and Nathaniel

552
00:33:02.894 --> 00:33:06.734
Gray's lab at Stanford, we now have an initial binder of

553
00:33:06.774 --> 00:33:10.414
DCAF5, and we have a big project going on to go after

554
00:33:10.453 --> 00:33:11.474
that.

555
00:33:12.414 --> 00:33:16.364
So I'll just go to the second to last bullet here that rather than

556
00:33:16.414 --> 00:33:19.934
causing a second toxicity with this synthetic

557
00:33:19.954 --> 00:33:20.614
lethality,

558
00:33:21.994 --> 00:33:25.774
targeting DCAF5 rescues the normal function and is

559
00:33:25.814 --> 00:33:29.214
essentially turning a cancer cell back to normal.

560
00:33:30.454 --> 00:33:34.294
They differentiate. And interesting, might this be true

561
00:33:34.354 --> 00:33:36.214
for other tumor suppressors?

562
00:33:37.794 --> 00:33:41.474
Now, I want to tell you now another story that was unpublished as I put this talk

